#{{{ Helpful Documentation
#
# standard colors
#
# Below are the color init strings for the basic file types. A color init
# string consists of one or more of the following numeric codes:
# Attribute codes:
# 00=none 01=bold 04=underscore 05=blink 07=reverse 08=concealed
# Text color codes:
# 30=black 31=red 32=green 33=yellow 34=blue 35=magenta 36=cyan 37=white
# Background color codes:
# 40=black 41=red 42=green 43=yellow 44=blue 45=magenta 46=cyan 47=white
#
#
# 256 color support
# see here: http://www.mail-archive.com/bug-coreutils@gnu.org/msg11030.html)
#
# Text 256 color coding:
# 38;5;COLOR_NUMBER
# Background 256 color coding:
# 48;5;COLOR_NUMBER
#}}}

#{{{ Notes on my strategy, and color codes/numbers
# - Blues, greens for files that open in apps: docx, xlsx, mpl, mscz, etc
#
# 01  | red              | #cc241d | orphan/broken symlinks
# 02  | green            | #98971a | executable
# 03  | yellow           | #d79921 | source (mpl)
# 04  | blue             | #458588 | powerpoint
# 05  | purple           | #b16286 | images
# 06  | aqua/cyan        | #689d6a | xlsx
# 07  | gray             | #a89984 | tex, wiki, song, md
# 08  | dark grey        | #928374 | default, configs
# 09  | bright red       | #fb4934 | archives
# 10  | bright green     | #b8bb26 | wav, flac audio
# 11  | bright yellow    | #fabd2f | source (js, py, lua)
# 12  | bright blue      | #83a598 | directories
# 13  | bright purple    | #d3869b | movies
# 14  | bright aqua/cyan | #8ec07c | mp3, lossy audio
# 15  | fg/white         | #ebdbb2 | txt, READMEs
# 67  | blue             | #5f87af | docx
# 94  | brown            | #875f00 | html
# 130 | light brown      | #af5f00 | sty
# 137 | very light brown | #af875f | pdf
# 143 | yellowgreen      | #afaf5f | csv
# 166 | orange           | #d75f00 | css
# 208 | orange           | #ff8700 | cls
# 239 | very dark grey   | #504945 | logs and backups
# 243 | darker grey      | #7c6f64 | git stuff
#}}}

#{{{ RULES

#{{{ BASIC sessings, Special files

NORMAL 00;38;5;15 #ebdbb2 fallback is "white" (foreground)
#FILE 00 # regular file: use no color at all
RESET 0 # reset to "normal" color
DIR 00;38;5;12 #83a598
LINK target
#LINK 00;38;5;37 # symbolic link. (If you set this to 'target' instead of a
 # numerical value, the color is as for the file pointed to.)
MULTIHARDLINK 00 # regular file with more than one link
FIFO 48;5;230;38;5;136;01 # pipe
SOCK 48;5;230;38;5;136;01 # socket
DOOR 48;5;230;38;5;136;01 # door
BLK 48;5;230;38;5;244;01 # block device driver
CHR 48;5;230;38;5;244;01 # character device driver
ORPHAN 00;38;5;160 # symlink to nonexistent file, or non-stat'able file
#ORPHAN 48;5;235;38;5;160 # symlink to nonexistent file, or non-stat'able file
SETUID 48;5;160;38;5;230 # file that is setuid (u+s)
SETGID 48;5;136;38;5;230 # file that is setgid (g+s)
CAPABILITY 30;41 # file with capability
STICKY_OTHER_WRITABLE 48;5;64;38;5;230 # dir that is sticky and other-writable (+t,o+w)
OTHER_WRITABLE 48;5;235;38;5;33 # dir that is other-writable (o+w) and not sticky
STICKY 48;5;33;38;5;230 # dir with the sticky bit set (+t) and not other-writable
# This is for files with execute permission:
EXEC 00;38;5;2 #98971a

#}}}

